For hard items, use 'scissors' twice to get the 'finely cut' feature, as one use of scissors on hard items will reduce their value. Framing is essential for maximizing value. Other combinations like natural soft with natural soft (cut) or artificial soft (cut) with artificial soft yield 45 points when framed.

This consistently yielded 45 value. Using scissors on 'hard' items with only one scissor results in negative value (-30). Combining two already framed items results in a very negative value. Pay close attention to item names in your inventory, as combined items can sometimes be listed by one of their original ingredient names (e.g., 'cut flower with mushroom' might just be 'mushroom').

message: The previous hint about 'natural soft' and 'artificial hard' is key! Look for single ingredients that are 'artificial, hard' (like buttons, beads). Combine 'natural, soft' (like flower, leaf, feather, mushroom) with an 'artificial, hard' item and then use the frame tool for a good score (e.g., flower + buttons -> frame). Also, 'natural, hard' items like wood benefit from 2 applications of scissors (wood -> cut wood -> finely cut wood), then combine the 'finely cut wood' (natural, hard) with an 'artificial, soft' item (like cardboard, paper) and then frame for potentially very high scores. Using scissors once on a single 'artificial, soft' item (like cardboard, thread) can also yield positive value, which you can then frame. Be careful not to use scissors multiple times on soft items, or on already framed items, as this often leads to negative values. Always frame a positive item if you have one, but avoid making items 'overcomplicated' with too many components. Good luck!
